dcac0a2d-ee5a-59eb-bb0b-12868e76a79f,tg:rubgr:2479,e73_Descriptions,,id.desc,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,"[recto] For P.B.II & Martin van Cleve see Marlier, Pierre Bruegel le Jeune, p. 333 ff. The Peasants attacked by Soldiers (Stockholm version, repr. Marlier, P.B.II, p. 275) signed and dated, according to Marlier, p. 276, P. BREVGHEL 1630. In letter from Karling, 30-5-73, the signature and date are given as P. Breugel 1626. According to Karling recent cleaning has revealed underneath this the signature ""BRUEGEL"" and below this the date MDLXV..; [toegevoegde vermelding]: 'F.G. But is this really a work of P.B.I? There are several factors which speak against Bruegel and rather for Martin van Cleve: 1) The open heath with its perspective appears in the Unfaithful Shepherd and it is unlikely that Bruegel simply repeated the background from another picture, unless one assumes the other way round that the Stockholm picture is an original & the background was copied in the Shepherd, where, however, it makes much more sense in connection with the fleeing figure. The copy in the Vienne Kh. Mus. has a different background.. The signature and date ""P.BREVGHEL 1558 appear, according to Marlier p. 276 on the Liechtensteinversion; 2) The Soldier attacking the woman with his foot is taken over from Bruegel's Massacre of the Innocents-again it; [verso] is not likely that Bruegel repeated himself, though it is sure there are differences between these two figures; 3) This figure shows the heave thick - set form of many of M. van Cleve's  later figures; 4) The young peasant - in his final features unlike Bruegel - has parallels in M. van Cleve's more ideal figures owing from his 'Floris' period; The figure group, with the soldier on the left attacking with a spear and the woman on the right is echoed in a drawing by Jacob de Gheyn II, 'a Landscape with robbers', signed and dated 1603, Munich, Staatliche Graphische Slg. (repr. J.G. van Gelder's: De Schoonheid van ons Land. Prenten en tekeningen, Amsterdam 1958, pl. 24). See also Munich Catalogue by Wegner [= Wolfgang Wegner, Die niederländischen Handzeichnungen des 15.-18. Jahrhunderts, 2 dln.,München1973]",descriptive note,Nederlands,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,

column4: <content>[recto] For P.B.II & Martin van Cleve see Marlier, Pierre Bruegel le Jeune, p. 333 ff. The Peasants attacked by Soldiers (Stockholm version, repr. Marlier, P.B.II, p. 275) signed and dated, according to Marlier, p. 276, P. BREVGHEL 1630. In letter from Karling, 30-5-73, the signature and date are given as P. Breugel 1626. According to Karling recent cleaning has revealed underneath this the signature ""BRUEGEL"" and below this the date MDLXV..; [toegevoegde vermelding]: 'F.G. But is this really a work of P.B.I? There are several factors which speak against Bruegel and rather for Martin van Cleve: 1) The open heath with its perspective appears in the Unfaithful Shepherd and it is unlikely that Bruegel simply repeated the background from another picture, unless one assumes the other way round that the Stockholm picture is an original & the background was copied in the Shepherd, where, however, it makes much more sense in connection with the fleeing figure. The copy in the Vienne Kh. Mus. has a different background.. The signature and date ""P.BREVGHEL 1558 appear, according to Marlier p. 276 on the Liechtensteinversion; 2) The Soldier attacking the woman with his foot is taken over from Bruegel's Massacre of the Innocents-again it; [verso] is not likely that Bruegel repeated himself, though it is sure there are differences between these two figures; 3) This figure shows the heave thick - set form of many of M. van Cleve's  later figures; 4) The young peasant - in his final features unlike Bruegel - has parallels in M. van Cleve's more ideal figures owing from his 'Floris' period; The figure group, with the soldier on the left attacking with a spear and the woman on the right is echoed in a drawing by Jacob de Gheyn II, 'a Landscape with robbers', signed and dated 1603, Munich, Staatliche Graphische Slg. (repr. J.G. van Gelder's: De Schoonheid van ons Land. Prenten en tekeningen, Amsterdam 1958, pl. 24). See also Munich Catalogue by Wegner [= Wolfgang Wegner, Die niederländischen Handzeichnungen des 15.-18. Jahrhunderts, 2 dln.,München1973]</content>
